Why .tabset and why it fails?

Interactive articles are more powerful to convey information to readers. Better visualisation helps readers to digest the content faster.

It is easy to include tabs in html article. The .tabset function can be included at a heading (say level 2) and all the following subheading (i.e.level 3) will be arranged in tabbed panels. However, this approach does not work with distill. This is confirmed in a 2018 post here but the authors did mention they wish to use jqueryUI tabsets in the future.

Note: This information is accurate as of 17th January 2022

Workaround

Garrik Aden-Buie suggested the panelset function from xaringanExtra to circumvent this issue, but the approach requires the fenced-div syntax as followed:

show code 
xaringanExtra::use_panelset()

# ::::: {.panelset}
#
# ::: {.panel}
#
# # Tab One {.panel-name}
#
# Content for tab one here
# 
# ### Sub heading one
#
# **Psst: see tab two!** 
#
# :::
#
# ::: {.panel}
#
# ## Tab Two {.panel-name}
#
# This is how I feel when I try to code
#
# ![](https://media.giphy.com/media/EJsTKyvaYzvm8/giphy.gif)
#
# :::
#
# ::: {.panel}
#
# ## Tab Three {.panel-name}
#
# Content for tab three here
#
# :::
#
# :::::
